The woods used in India for ship-building are, teak, saul, sissoo, jarrol, poon,
                    and toon. Teak is the most durable among these timbers, but it varies very much
                    in quality. There are two kinds of the Malabar teak, the northern and southern;
                    the first is far superior in point of durability, but is the most difficult to
                    procure. The Malabar teak is classed at Bombay as follows. No. 1, Northern,
                    curved timber, which is brought a distance from Bombay of from 130 to 140 miles;
                    No. 2, Southern, Calicut teak;
